<h3 class=3D"kt-adv-heading17_14421f-87 wp-block-kadence-advancedheading" d=
ata-kb-block=3D"kb-adv-heading17_14421f-87">Know Your Worth (and Set an Hou=
rly Rate)</h3>



<p>First things first: How much is your time worth? If you worked a =E2=80=
=9Cregular=E2=80=9D job, what would you expect to earn per hour? </p>



<p>$10? $15? $20 or more? </p>



<p>My advice? Start with at least the minimum wage in your area=E2=80=94cro=
chet isn=E2=80=99t just a craft; it=E2=80=99s a physically demanding skill.=
</p>



<p>Think about it: Your hands, wrists, back, and shoulders all work hard on=
 every project, and that labor deserves fair compensation. </p>



<p>You=E2=80=99re putting your energy, creativity, and hours into each piec=
e, so don=E2=80=99t sell yourself short.</p>



<p>But what if I=E2=80=99m not the fastest crocheter? </p>



<p>That=E2=80=99s okay! </p>



<p>Speed isn=E2=80=99t the measure of worth =E2=80=93 The quality of your w=
ork, your skill, and your attention to detail are what truly matter.</p>



<p>Spend some time thinking about this because you=E2=80=99ll need it to us=
e our crochet calculator later on.</p>



<h3 class=3D"kt-adv-heading17_508c41-cb wp-block-kadence-advancedheading" d=
ata-kb-block=3D"kb-adv-heading17_508c41-cb">Track Your Time and Labor</h3>



<p>Once you=E2=80=99ve decided on your hourly rate, it=E2=80=99s time to ge=
t serious about tracking your hours. </p>



<p>This step might seem tedious at first, but trust me=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s=
 a game-changer.</p>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s how to do it:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Use a notebook, a spreadsheet, or even your phone=E2=80=99s timer to re=
cord the time spent on each project.</li>



<li>Be honest with yourself! If you worked on it for 10 minutes here and 30=
 minutes there, it all adds up.</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Let=E2=80=99s do a quick example:</strong></p>



<p>Say you=E2=80=99ve set your hourly rate at $10, and it takes you 8 hours=
 to crochet a baby blanket. </p>



<p>That=E2=80=99s <strong>$80 for your time</strong>=E2=80=94just for the l=
abor. </p>



<p>This number isn=E2=80=99t optional; it=E2=80=99s the foundation of your =
pricing.</p>



<p>Why is tracking so important?</p>



<p>Your time is your value. </p>



<p>It=E2=80=99s the only variable that you won=E2=80=99t be able to reasona=
bly alter. </p>



<p>You may be able to get discounts on yarn, patterns, resources, or materi=
als, but your time is valuable enough to fully charge for it.</p>



<p>When you clearly account for your hours, you=E2=80=99re sending a messag=
e: <em>This work has value, and I=E2=80=99m worth it.</em></p>



<p>This is another key element when using our crochet calculator, and it ma=
kes a huge difference in your pricing model.</p>



<h3 class=3D"kt-adv-heading17_7c3e0c-d0 wp-block-kadence-advancedheading" d=
ata-kb-block=3D"kb-adv-heading17_7c3e0c-d0">Include Materials and Extras</h=
3>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s where many crocheters stumble=E2=80=94they forget to fact=
or in the costs of yarn, tools, packaging, and even shipping. Let=E2=80=99s=
 fix that!</p>



<p>Think of it this way: You=E2=80=99re running a business, not a charity (=
even if crochet sometimes feels like a labor of love). </p>



<p>Every dollar you spend to create a project should be added to your prici=
ng.</p>



<p><strong>For example:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Did you spend $20 on yarn? Add it.</li>



<li>Did you ship the item for $6? Add that too.</li>



<li>Don=E2=80=99t forget about packaging, tags, or any little extras that w=
ent into the project.</li>
</ul>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s a quick breakdown:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Labor</strong>: $80 (8 hours x $10/hour)</li>



<li><strong>Materials</strong>: $20 (for yarn or tools)</li>



<li><strong>Shipping/Packaging</strong>: $6</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Total Price:</strong> $106</p>



<p>Now, if $106 seems like a lot for a baby blanket, stop and think about w=
hat you=E2=80=99re really offering:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>This isn=E2=80=99t a cheap, mass-produced product.</li>



<li>This is a one-of-a-kind, handmade piece of art that someone will treasu=
re.</li>



<li>You=E2=80=99re exchanging hours of your life, skill, and love for incom=
e.</li>
</ul>



<p>Still feeling unsure?</p>



<p>Consider this: If someone truly values your work, they=E2=80=99ll pay fo=
r it. </p>



<p>Your pricing doesn=E2=80=99t just reflect the cost of materials=E2=80=94=
it reflects the worth of your time. </p>



<p>If someone balks at the price, they=E2=80=99re not your customer, and th=
at=E2=80=99s okay!&nbsp;</p>



<p>Knowing your actual material costs will factor into the crochet calculat=
or when pricing your projects.</p>



<p><strong>Final Thoughts</strong>:</p>



<p>Pricing can be intimidating, but it=E2=80=99s also empowering. </p>



<p>By knowing your worth, tracking your time, and factoring in materials, y=
ou=E2=80=99re taking control of your business and honoring the hard work yo=
u put into every stitch.</p>



<p>Remember, this is about valuing your time and skill. </p>



<p>So the next time someone asks, =E2=80=9CHow much for this?=E2=80=9D you =
can confidently share your price, knowing it=E2=80=99s fair for both of you=
. You=E2=80=99ve got this!&nbsp;</p>



